# Adyen Workshop — Code Documentation Standards

This is an **educational** project (Adyen partner training). The reader will come back weeks
later and re-learn the payments integration by reading the code. Therefore every file we
write or modify MUST be commented generously and with links to Adyen documentation.

## File header (REQUIRED in every Java / JS / HTML file we touch)

Keep it short — 3–5 lines, not a wall of text.

**Java** (above the `package` declaration is fine, or as `/** */` above the class):

```java
/**
 * <ClassName> — <one-line purpose>
 * Workshop step(s): <e.g. Step 7, Step 9, Step 12>
 * Adyen docs:       <https://docs.adyen.com/...>
 * What & Why:       <one line explaining role in the payment flow>
 */
```

**JavaScript** (top of file):

```javascript
/**
 * <file purpose> — <one-line summary>
 * Workshop step(s): <e.g. Step 8, Step 10>
 * Adyen docs:       <https://docs.adyen.com/...>
 * What & Why:       <Drop-in role: fetches /paymentMethods, mounts component, handles onSubmit>
 */
```

**HTML / Thymeleaf** (top of file as `<!-- -->`):

```html
<!--
  <template name> — <purpose>
  Workshop step: <e.g. Step 6>
  Why: <e.g. "loads Adyen.Web Drop-in script + stylesheet for all pages">
-->
```

## Inline / line-level comments (the core of this rule)

For every **non-trivial** line or small block of Adyen-specific code, add a comment with:
1. **What** it does in one short phrase
2. **Why** we do it that way (the *reason*, not the syntax)
3. **Link** to Adyen docs when the line corresponds to an Adyen concept (`/payments`, `3DS2`, `HMAC`, `idempotency`, `BrowserInfo`, `returnUrl`, etc.)

Place the comment on the line above, in English.

### Good vs bad examples

```java
// BAD — narrates syntax, adds no understanding
// create a new payment request
var paymentRequest = new PaymentRequest();

// GOOD — explains intent + links the relevant doc
// Build the /payments request body. We re-create it on every call (stateless) and let
// the Adyen Java library handle JSON serialization.
// Docs: https://docs.adyen.com/api-explorer/Checkout/latest/post/payments
var paymentRequest = new PaymentRequest();

// GOOD — explains *why* a constant value was chosen
// Hard-coded EUR 99.98 because the demo store sells items at €49.99 × 2.
// Amount.value is in *minor units* (cents) per Adyen API convention.
// Docs: https://docs.adyen.com/development-resources/currency-codes/
var amount = new Amount().currency("EUR").value(9998L);

// GOOD — flags a security/correctness concern
// SECURITY: returnUrl must match an Allowed origin on the Client Key, otherwise
// Adyen will reject the 3DS2 redirect.
paymentRequest.setReturnUrl("http://localhost:8080/handleShopperRedirect");
```

```javascript
// BAD
// fetch payment methods
const res = await fetch("/api/paymentMethods", { method: "POST" });

// GOOD
// Ask our backend for the list of payment methods configured on this merchant
// account. The backend forwards this to Adyen's /paymentMethods endpoint
// (we never call Adyen directly from the browser — API key must stay server-side).
// Docs: https://docs.adyen.com/online-payments/build-your-integration/advanced-flow/#post-payment-methods-request
const res = await fetch("/api/paymentMethods", { method: "POST" });
```

## Special tags (use when relevant)

- `// SECURITY:` — anything involving API key, HMAC, Client Key origins, returnUrl, CSRF
- `// CRITICAL:` — idempotency, ordering of operations, must-not-skip steps
- `// NOTE:` — educational context (e.g. "this is what 3DS2 frictionless flow looks like")
- `// DOCS:` — when a whole block deserves a doc link rather than per-line
- `// TODO:` / `// FIXME:` — only for genuine follow-ups, never as a substitute for explanation

## What NOT to comment

Skip captain-obvious narration of the language itself:

- `// constructor` above a constructor
- `// import statement` above an import
- `// return the response` above `return ResponseEntity.ok().body(response);`
- `// loop over items` above a `for` loop with a self-evident name

Comment the **Adyen domain**, not the **Java/JS syntax**.

## Section dividers for long files

When a file grows past ~80 lines, use simple dividers:

```java
// === Step 7: /paymentMethods =================================================
```

```javascript
// === Step 10: onSubmit handler ===============================================
```

## When editing existing code

If you change a line that has an outdated comment, **update the comment in the same edit**.
A stale comment is worse than no comment.

